title: Flexible laser cut Cristmas tree ornaments

description.text: Something that always amazes FabLab visitors, is flexible wood. By laser cutting special patterns in the wood, it is possible to make the wood flex without breaking. Aaron Porterfield has created an instructable with different patterns to create flexible wood (http://www.instructables.com/id/Curved-laser-bent-wood/). The flexibility of the wood is dependent on the thickness of the wood, the shape of the pattern and the size of the pattern. You can read more about the physics: http://www.deferredprocrastination.co.uk/blog/category/def-proc/lattice-hinges/ Today, I made some flexible Christmas ornaments for the Christmas tree. We will need some general geometry and of course the flexibility patterns. I will cut the ornaments in 3mm MDF. If you want to create flexibility patterns for other materials or another material thickness, you will need to experiment with the pattern dimensions. To read more about I created the patterns in Inkscape, go to my blog: http://make.petervdb.be/2015/12/23/flexible-christmas-ornaments/

title: Height adjustable router support for rotary tool

description.text:
This gadget converts your rotary tool (i.e. Dremel) to a handy router. The inner thread of this gadget is compatible with most Dremel-like tools. The height can be adjusted by turning the knob part. The thread pitch of the adjustable mechanism is 2 mm so each half a turn lifts the tool 1 mm. Total movement of the lift is around 20 mm depending the machine is used. I've tested the gadget with Bosch GRO 10,8 v. See an example groove cut on Youtube:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2-ibSAT9J0E

A simple character, a basic over weight brat of a dragon child that kind of plays as one of the comedic foils in the storyline of the game itself.  More likely than not this is not going to be the final design of the character so I feel confadent sharing him with everyone.  Also makes me feel accomplished by turning some silly concept in my mind and making it real.
Also, this is the first thing that I've designed that I printed on my 3D printer, so I decided to share the chubby brat with everyone else.
Not to mention those tiny wings might also serve as a test of your printer's accuracy and support structure building.

Use support structure, probably at around 40 degrees maybe.
Also, the bottom of the model isn't perfectly flat.
Another quick warning, I don't know if he will fit on a cupcake with support material.  I 'bet' he can but I can not conferm it.

title: LG Sunrise Smartphone Holder (for the WalMart $10 TracFone)

description.text:
The clip currently fits the phone perfectly. I am planning it to be used as inexpensive WiFi-IP cameras using the free Android app "IP Webcam". I have included 2 types of brackets that provide several mounting options. You may need to play with the order you assemble the bracket and pivot depending the angles you want to be able to pivot to, and whether you want the bracket "above" or "below" the camera. Use the small square mounting bracket if you want a low-profile mount to screw onto something like a wall. Use the large triangular mount with pins if you want to attach it to glass with suction-cups, or discard the pins and you can use it as a stand/base. Printing:
  • I recommend printing the main camera clip "on edge" so that every layer follows the contour that the phone fits in, this will prevent sagging or deformation in some of the parts. The other pieces probably don't matter as much.
  • I recommend a wide 5mm brim, especially for the triangular mounting point. This provides maximum bed adhesion and minimum warping. Clean up sharp edges with a file after pealing the brim off.
    • Assembly:
  • Use a 9/64" drill (or 1/8 with some "working" it bigger) to finish the screw holes to fit a #6-32 screw.
  • Assemble the bracket and pivot pieces using 6-32 x 3/4" screws with matching nuts (washers will not fit without modification due to small tolerances but they are not required).
  • If you use suction cups with the triangular mount, it is designed to fit "DORMAN 1355" type found at my local WalMart, remove plastic "J" hook from the center hole and feed the suction cup into the hole in the mount. Secure the suction cup with one of the pins (there should be 1 extra pin) by feeding the pin along the raised track and thru the center hole of the suction-cup. The pins are semi-circular, ensure the flat part faces the mount, this should fit the suction-cup exactly and "snap" into the raised edges on the mounting plate.
    • Addons:
    To make your own "brackets" that will fit my part, you should have a "semi-circle" type mounting post. It should be up to 7mm wide with a 1.5mm hole in the middle to align with the one in the phone bracket.

The first version with a rounded upper handle did not print the rounded part of the handle or the spiked detail in the arms. It all printed up to same level as that which the M sits on. It's functional but not as in the first stl image here. The side where the detail was, with the M, printed only a membrane of a final layer so I reinforced that with black nail polish and did some detail designs with metallic nail polish. The picture is of the failed print. The "2" stl is a quick fix I made to the file to get rid of the curved handle that was causing problems. I have not printed this but should be ok. My son liked it as a gift but he did not like the messy rubber bands. I took one of my daughter's headbands, cut it open, sewed both ends in loops, and stretched those over the posts. I have used this arm for some time now and major crashes have not even phased it. The arm has integrated spacers and strain-relief. The main section of the arm is 4.7mm thick and stretches to 10mm at the base. The arm has a channel for routing the motor wires through. The strain relief reduces stress at the normal pinch point of the frame. These arms are much lighter than the thick replacement carbon fiber arms they now sell. I have broken the thin arms that come with the frame - These I have not broken. Thin (3mm) carbon fiber (stock) and spacers: 9.6g each Printed arm with spacer and strain-relief: 14.5g each Thicker (5mm) carbon fiber and spacers: 18.7g each Sure you could pay $50 for the thicker carbon fiber, but you can print this on-demand in any color for about 50 cents and save on about 4g weight each. Print at 100% infill. For strength, print the infill at a 45 degree angle. Remove the integrated skirt/brim after printing.
